We learned to walk, talk, and read books (he had dozens of children's books) we learned our colors, numbers, alphabet together, from Sesame Street, Mr. Rogers, Make a Wish, and Let's All Sing a Song Today.  As we enjoyed discovering the world around us, I knew I was teaching him, but never expected how much HE was teaching ME! The lessons I learned from my son served me well in my subsequent education and career as a nurse.  I was priveliged to witness and assist in several deliveries, even though saddened that so many of them were single mothers surrounded by strangers.   I am profoundly saddened when I see so many single mothers of young children, since for most of these broken families, there is a father bereft of the delights of children sharing their lives.  If these dads only knew what they were missing, the divorce rate might vanish altogether.   On the other hand, I remember seeing a family of four in the emergency room with two small chidren being constantly but softly sung-to by their father.  Sadly, these days, much parental attention is circumvented by the parents' addiction to cell phone "conversations" until their children are old enough to play their own video games.  I am saddened when I see 3-4 member families eating a restaurant meal without a word of conversation, EVERY ONE transfixed by their smartphones.  If I could give  one piece of advice to new parents it would be TURN OFF YOUR PHONES, fron 5 minutes to an hour or two EVERY DAY for "special time" together, reading a bedtime story, singing a lulaby, discussing each other's joys, sorrows, fears and triumphs as well as sharing each day's experiences.    You and your other half may be pure happenstance beneficiaries of the most precious gift imaginable by having your baby together and possibly a very long time to share early childhood.

Okay, good advice all the way... AND God... I hate to bitch about it, BUT we live in a sad reality where there simply aren't enough test swabs and kits to get around as it is. I'm in an area where I can't justify taking up NOT ONE, BUT TWO swabs to ensure I'm "safe" to be in the public again after I've been sick... It would be fan-damn-tastic to find a "rule of thumb" about self-isolating until you're something like 90% likely or better to be safe before going out again... being with people physically again.      Lots of us are GOING to be denied these kits no matter what we do or try. That's a fact... AND taking up the cash to get a kit "by hook or crook" could deny someone else (who desperately needs it?) the access when they could just have a sniffle or be coming down with something catastrophic without knowing it...       With the flu, for instance, common advice is "If you don't have a fever, you're probably not contagious."... BUT with Covid-19, that's not the case. Surely, around now, someone has a figure "in the ball park" that we can follow to do better than "reasonably confident" we're no longer contagious if we suspect we've recovered from this thing. I don't like the idea of accidentally spreading "plague" on people who might be immuno-compromised, at risk, or what have you... BUT maybe a crude guideline is better than nothing... I don't know... Something like "Take 3 weeks out instead of 2 to be sure" or "Add two weeks past your fever's break"... and a person could reasonably consider forgoing the waste of TWO more swabs the rest of society can't afford to piss away... just to say "yeah, you're fine."  ;o)

I supervise 16 sterile compounding technicians.  We can't compound sterile product from home, so they are all reporting to work, making 700 to 1000 doses a day for our patients.   One of them is on medical leave (unrelated to covid-19), so she can't work...but she can sow - so she volunteered to help with making reusable masks for health systems in our area.  She also volunteered her services as childcare for two of our workers who couldn't find anything, so they can be at work.   The director for our region has been meeting with us via teleconference daily to help coordinate and answer questions, and personally served as delivery driver of thousands of masks made by a retooled furniture manufacturer to help provide relief.   This was particularly moving to me, because I had one of my staff at my desk today, crying with guilt, because we have masks when others don't.  I had to walk them through exactly why masks have been allocated to our work (an on-going assessment as things develop).  We can kill our patients if we don't maintain our clean-room standards, or almost as bad, cause them to be hospitalized, adding burden to an overburdened system.   I have been continually humbled and honored to work with my team and the rest of our company as we strive to keep our 800 plus patients out of the hospital system and safe at home.
